<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06189036 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06189036 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Burt Reynolds and Dinah Shore trade stories and admiring lookson TNN  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY; MAN; WOMAN; PAST; RELATION; TELEVISION; INTERVIEW; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  FEEL like eavesdropping on one of the best conversations of 1991?;    Thentune in to watch Dinah Shore and Burt Reynolds, two very high-profile loversin the early 1970s, as they get back together this Wednesday night in one ofthe most entertaining TV shows you'll see this year.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  TV Magazine  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SOMEONE'S IN THE STUDIO WITH DINAH  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  CableDINAH SHORE: A SPECIAL CONVERSATION WITH BURT REYNOLDSWednesday at 5 and 8 p.m., Nashville Network  </MEMO><TEXT>     In this 90-minute special edition of Shore's talk show on cable's TheNashville Network (TNN), Shore and Reynolds just reminisce about the six yearsthey spent together -- along with the company of maybe 10 or 15 milliontabloid newspaper readers.;    In those days, inquiring readers wanted to knowif a handsome male movie star could find happiness with a famous singer whowas 19 years older.;    Though their well-documented affair didn't end inmarriage, it's obvious Reynolds and Shore have remained close friends eversince. So close, in fact, that they hold hands all through their chat and windup in several fervent clinches.;    Reynolds, who's now 55 and married toactress Loni Anderson, grins through Shore's opening remarks about how theirrelationship ended in &quot;respect and friendship.&quot;;    &quot;I'm looking forward tothis -- I think,&quot; he says, hugging Shore closely and telling her she still&quot;smells the same.&quot;;    &quot;Is that good?&quot; asks Shore, who's 74 and still lookinggood. He assures her it is.;    Reynolds recalls how they met 20 years ago andhow they tried to keep his parents from knowing they &quot;were doing it&quot; wheneverthey visited them in Florida. Apparently, they weren't fooling anyone,including Reynolds' folks.;    Once the two friends get rolling, they seem toforget about the studio audience and just start trading anecdotes about eachother. Among the best:;    (check) Reynolds tells about the time Shore cookeda steak on a hot plate and gave them both food poisoning.;    &quot;We both racedfor the bathroom,&quot; he says. &quot;There was only one. As I recall, I let you gofirst.&quot;;    (check) Shore recalls &quot;training&quot; Reynolds for his singing-dancingdebut in the disastrous musical &quot;At Long Last Love&quot; with Cybill Shepherd.;   &quot;I was drunk the whole picture,&quot; he recalls.;    (check) Reynolds also tellsabout the time he and actor Ned Beatty tried to recreate the harrowingwhite-water rafting scene from their hit film &quot;Deliverance&quot; by going down thesame turbulent river in a rubber raft.;    (check) Shore tells aboutaccidentally getting locked behind bars with a hard-case felon while visitingReynolds on the Georgia prison location for &quot;The Longest Yard.&quot;;    Theirpublic sharing of good times together seems to bring both to the verge oftears on several occasions. At one point, Reynolds appears to struggle forcontrol as he tells the viewing audience how much Shore has meant to him.;   &quot;If I have any class in my career,&quot; he says to Shore, &quot;it came from you.&quot;;   Shore seems equally moved and explains how valuable their romance was to herat a time when she needed renewed confidence in herself, both as a singer andas a woman.;    &quot;We gave each other so much,&quot; says Shore.;    In this warm,witty and bittersweet reunion, they also wind up giving us quite a bit aswell. (box)  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RON MILLER, Mercury News Television Editor  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910707  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  553  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday July 7, 199100189036,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>